Crested wood partridges are rotund short-tailed members of the pheasant family native to Southeast Asia. Males sport tall red crests while females have pea green plumage with chestnut brown wing coverts. These partridges live in a rainforest biome at the Eden Project in Cornwall.

The silky anteater is the world's smallest anteater, with adults averaging less than 1 pound and just over 1 foot in length. They spend most of their lives in the trees, climbing with a prehensile tail and sizable claws.
During winter, Dark-eyed Juncos form fairly large flocks. Flocks typically have a hierarchy or pecking order, and earlier arrivals tend to rank higher in the group than later arrivals

Chemicals on ants' feet tranquilise and subdue colonies of aphids, keeping them close-by as a ready source of food. The aphids produce a sugary substance called honeydew as a waste product, which ants love to eat!

This is a 3 day old snapping turtle. Snapping turtles lay their eggs on land and are often predated/disturbed. Their sex is determined by the temp of their egg during incubation. This baby still has it's egg tooth.

Crossbills are characterized by the mandibles crossing at their tips, which gives the group its English name. Using their crossed mandibles for leverage, crossbills are able to efficiently separate the scales of conifer cones and extract the seeds on which they feed.

Skilton's skink, a subspecies of the western skink, is native to the US west of the Rocky Mountains as well as to southern British Columbia, Canada. These skinks possess bright blue tails as juveniles, but the color fades to gray into adulthood. Skinks will often regrow a tail if it breaks off.

This is a bongo, a large forest antelope native to western and central Africa. They experience sexual dimorphism where females, such as this one, have the chestnut colored hide and males have dark brown hides

The Cape sparrow mostly eats seeds, foraging in trees and on the ground. The larger seeds of cereals, wild grasses, and other small plants are preferred, with wheat and khakiweed (Alternanthera caracasana) being favourites.

Sand cats are well adapted to life in the desert, with thick fur on its paws to protect against hot sand and a body that can conserve water. It is also known for its ability to survive without drinking water for long periods of time, getting most of its moisture from the food it eats.

The most widely distributed pinniped, the harbor seal or common seal (Phoca vitulina) is found along temperate and arctic coastlines throughout the northern hemisphere. A thick layer of blubber helps these chonkers thrive in cold waters.
Alpacas are social, herd animals - enjoy company - and communicate with soft humming sounds. And each one has a personality! 😍
Wrinkled-face bats are from Central America, and eat fruit with their strong bite force. Males emit an intense odor from their chin to attract females.

In groups of Banded mongooses all females give birth in the same night, this way no female knows wich pups are hers. This stops females from prioritizing their pups and discriminating agains, or disposing of those of other females. This leads to a fair treatment of all pups.
Horses are able to recognize themselves in mirrors, this strongly hints at self awareness.
The red-eyed tree frog lives 5 years. When the eggs are ready to hatch, the tadpoles inside start swirling around vigorously. The activity breaks each egg open, releasing the little tadpoles.

The yellowhammer adds invertebrates to its diet in the breeding season, particularly as food for its growing chicks. A wide range of species is taken, including springtails, grasshoppers, flies, beetles, caterpillars, earthworms, spiders, and snails.

Both male and female Inca terns sport a stylish "moustache" of white satiny feathers that sprout from the base of the beak. The individuals with the longest moustaches are also generally the healthiest and most productive birds.

An Asian giant softshell turtle will spend up to 95% of its life buried motionless under the mud of slow-running streams. It will ambush fish and crustaceans that wander within range of its long neck, thrusting its head forward with great speed. It only surfaces to breathe twice daily.

Fringe-lipped bats (Trachops cirrhosus) are very smart and hunt frogs by listening to the chunking sounds male frogs make. They are also easily trained to respond to novel stimuli, such as a ringtone or rock music, and can remember the sounds for years.

When a yellowjacket steals some of your food it's not for them, it's for their larvae! The adult will chew the food then bring it back to the nest to share it with the larvae. The larvae in turn produce a sugary substance the adults feed on. This exchange is known as trophallaxis.

Tawny frogmouths are masters of camouflage, using their plumage to stay hidden in trees during the day. They will also emulate broken tree branches by sticking their necks out, closing their eyes, and remaining perfectly still. They may look like grumpy owls but are actually related to nightjars.
Basenjis were one of the first ever dog breeds. Instead of barking, they yodel. They also groom themselves like cats sometimes. Basenjis are also rare dog breeds.

The snout of Tyrannosaurus Rex was line with special pressure sensors like Crocodilians that would've given them great control over their jaws, they could carry their eggs and young without the risk of harming them and as a byproduct would very sensitive to touch. (Prehistoric Planet)
Giant pandas are the only bears with grasping paws! Instead of opposable thumbs, an elongated wrist bone acts as a sixth finger to let them hold bamboo more easily.

The Colugo, also known as a "Flying Lemur:" these mammals are able to glide through the air using a fur-covered membrane that stretches along their cheeks, limbs, fingertips, sides, and tail; as a baby, a colugo must cling to its mother's belly as she glides from tree-to-tree
this is the domesticated silk Moth, the main reason it's so white is that years of domestication has made it lose all of its pigment and ability to fly, still very cute Moth anyway

Rainbow parrotfish inhabit coral reefs, mangroves and shallow seagrass beds of the western Atlantic Ocean. They can grow to 1.2 m (3.9 ft) in length, weigh up to 20 kg (44 lbs) and live to 16 years old. These rainbow parrotfish were filmed by Coral City Camera at an "urban coral reef" in Miami.

Satin bowerbirds are not in the least finicky in their food preferences, and have taken extremely readily to numerous plants introduced since European settlement. They are a major dispersal agent for a number of weedy plants, such as camphor laurel, the European olive and various species of privet

Lamarckdromia Crabs: these fluffy crabs make their own protective "hats" out of living sea sponges; after selecting a suitable sponge, the crab trims it down to the right size, drapes the tailored sponge across its carapace, and carries it around

When the yellow box fish becomes alarmed or is threatened, it reacts by blowing itself up to appear more dangerous and releasing a cloud of a powerful toxin that will kill any fish in the immediate surroundings. By the way, this toxin is also lethal to other yellow boxfish (and themselves!)
Earwigs (Dermaptera) are generally very attentive mothers. They defend and regularly clean their eggs. If provided with eggs from another earwig, they will also care for those eggs/nymphs.

The Przewalski's horse is the last non-feral wild horse in the world. They are stockier than most domestic horses and have short erect mane (similar to donkeys and zebras) and sometimes have faint stripes on the legs.
Barred Owls don’t migrate, and they don’t even move around very much. Of 158 birds that were banded and then found later, none had moved farther than 6 miles away.

The Numbat aka the banded anteater, is a small pouchless insect-eating marsupial native to Australia. It grows to about 29.5-50 cm including its bushy tail. Numbat has a long sticky tongue that allows it to pick up termites, which is its primary diet. An adult numbat needs up to 20K termites daily.

Though sheep have a structured social order, introducing sheep to one another typically does not lead to too much drama! It’s rare for sheep to have interpersonal issues that aren’t solved by avoiding one another as long as they have enough space to do so, which is easy to do at sanctuaries. ❤️
Phainopepla spread mistletoe by eating the berries and wiping the seeds on branches. The seeds then germinate and the plant haustoria, kind of like roots, dig into the branch and grow to a new plant.

The tufted titmouse is a small songbird from North America, a species in the tit and chickadee family (Paridae). The black-crested titmouse, found from central and southern Texas southward, was included as a subspecies but now is considered a separate species, Baeolophus atricristatus.
Morpho rhetenor, the Rhetenor blue morpho, is a Neotropical butterfly of the family Nymphalidae. It is found in Suriname, French Guiana, Brazil, Peru, Ecuador, Colombia, and Venezuela.

The leaf sheep (costasiella kuroshimae) is a sea slug that is able to photosynthesize. It does this by consuming algae and retaining the chloroplasts from the algae in its own tissues. This allows it to produce its own food through photosynthesis, which is unusual for an animal.

The American robin's diet generally consists of around 40 percent small invertebrates (mainly insects), such as earthworms, beetle grubs, caterpillars and grasshoppers, and 60 percent wild and cultivated fruits and berries.
Argentina's patagonian maras only go into estrus (heat) a few times a year and only for a half-hour at a time. They are monogamous and will mate for life, rarely leaving each other's side.

Meet Blackberry 👋 1 of just 73 remaining critically endangered Southern Resident Orca. These orca are extremely social creatures, tail slaps are often used for communication, celebration, hunting, and play.

Great tits are primarily insectivorous in the summer, feeding on insects and spiders which they capture by foliage gleaning. Their larger invertebrate prey include cockroaches, grasshoppers and crickets, lacewings, earwigs, bugs (Hemiptera), ants, flies (Diptera), caddis flies, beetles, scorpions...

The Maned wolf (Chrysocyon Br.), although they live very solitary lives in the wild, are surprisingly one of the few Canid species that are monogamous and mate for life. They will often share their territory w/ each other and the males often stay to help protect their offspring from other predators.

The Bengal cat is a relatively modern hybrid breed of domestic cat (since the 1980's) stemming primarily from crossing the spotted Egyptian Mau, the Asian leopard cat and several other breeds. A Bengal cat with a highly rosetted coat bearing a strong color contrast is often called a clouded Bengal.

North America’s littlest falcon, the American Kestrel, can keep their eyes focused on their prey, insects and other small prey in open territory, even if they're perched on a branch or wire in the breeze, thanks to this ability to stabilize its head.
Echidna’s long tongue have lots of blood vessels, when tongue is engorged with blood, the tongue is stiffened and stretch out, resemble another erectile tissue.

Ring in the New Year! The Asian Elephant primarily resides around the Indian Subcontinent. Fiercely intelligent, they have a highly developed neocortex not unlike humans, apes, and dolphins. Twin births are rare. Births where both calves survive are even rarer especially in captivity.

The water anole is unique in that it is able to stay underwater for long periods of time - a behavior that is described as “scuba diving.” Experiments have confirmed that this species has the ability to remain underwater for up to 16 minutes

The short-beaked echidna has the largest prefrontal cortex relative to body size of any mammal, taking up 50% of cortex volume in comparison to 29% for humans. Based on studies, scientists have concluded its learning ability is similar to that of a cat or a rat. This echidna is searching for ants.

The Australian owlet-nightjar, native to Australia and New Guinea, is a nocturnal bird that roosts in tree hollows during the day. It is colloquially known as the moth owl. The owlet-nightjar feeds at night by diving from perches and snatching insects from the air in the manner of a flycatcher.
Egret grow delicate, filamentous plume in breeding season, which called aigrettes

The Japanese serow is a goat-antelope that roams the dense woodlands of Japan. A skillful mountain dweller, it is able to sprint up slopes swiftly and leap from cliff to cliff nimbly. Hunters of this animal have compared its abilities to that of a ninja.

Cicadas are a superfamily of insects, the Cicadoidea, which number over 3000 species. Many of these species are known for their exceptionally loud buzzing sounds which are produced by vibrating tymbals located on their abdomens. An entomologist provides more details about one particular species.

Snakes do not have the right kind of teeth to chew their food so they must eat their food whole. The jaws of snakes are not fused to the skull, so the lower jaw can separate from the upper jaw. This allows their mouths to open wider than their own bodies in order to swallow their prey whole.
A newly born Green Anole. These little guys have to fend for themselves from the get-go, and also stay away from other larger reptiles and mammals as they could eat them.

The broad-billed hummingbird eats both nectar and insects. The hummingbird is also known to visit sugar-water hummingbird feeders. Their eating habits showed that the broad-billed hummingbird prefers visiting red or red-and-yellow flowers the most.

Recent tracking studies have revealed that oystercatchers make tremendously variable movements after the breeding season. Young birds do not follow their parents to wintering locations; in fact, young from the same nest may even migrate in completely different directions in autumn.

The silky sifaka is one of the world's rarest lemurs, having only been identified as a separate species in 2000s. Males can be distinguished from the pure white females by their brown chest patches, which results from scent marking with a gland on the sternum.

Often thought of as solitary animals, new observations and research are proving that jaguars are very social creatures. This is the Cuachicqueh coalition, a coalition of two young males from the Pantanal that have been seen patrolling and hunting together. More information in the comments.
Jellyfish nematocyst discharge can take only a few microseconds. Recent research suggests the process can occur as fast as 700 nanoseconds, thus reaching an acceleration of up to 5,410,000 g.
Bearded Vulture aka Lammergeier/Ossifrage chicks take 100-130 days to leave their nest and require parental care for 2yrs, forcing their parents to nest on alternating years on a regular basis.
Despite commonly being portrayed as vicious predators, Nile Crocodiles are caring parents who guard their nest and even help their hatchlings hatch

The Inca tern (Larosterna inca) is a distinctive seabird found along the coasts of Peru and Chile. With its black body, white mustache-like facial markings, bright red-orange beak and feet, and a prominent crest on its head, the Inca tern possesses a striking appearance.

Mourning doves eat almost exclusively seeds, which make up more than 99% of their diet. Rarely, they will eat snails or insects. Mourning doves generally eat enough to fill their crops and then fly away to digest while resting

While the okapi might appear to be a hybrid of a horse and a zebra, this elusive forest dweller is actually the only living relative of the giraffe. Male okapi have fuzzy horns, similar to those of a giraffe, and long dark tongues - longer than a giraffes, at 30-36 cm (12-14 inches).

The snowshoe hare is co-called because of the large size of its hind feet which prevents it from sinking into the snow. Its feet also have a layer of fur on the soles to protect from frostbite. During the summer, these hares are rusty brown but as winter approaches, they take on a white pelage.

The western jackdaw tends to feed on small invertebrates up to 18 millimetres (0.71 in) in length that are found above ground, including various species of beetle (particularly cockchafers of the genus Melolontha, and weevil larvae and pupae. Diptera, and Lepidoptera species, snails and spiders.

Despite common belief, grass is not the preferred food for whitetail or other deer. Less that 10% of their diet is grass, and generally they enjoy it in the spring when the fresh shoots are young and tender, and are often foraging for fresh weeds rather than grass.

Steller's jays are omnivores; their diet is about two-thirds plant matter and one-third animal matter. They gather food both from the ground and from trees. Their diet includes a wide range of seeds, nuts, berries and other fruit, as well as invertebrates, small rodents, eggs, and nestlings.

Helmeted Guineafowl is a gregarious species, forming flocks outside the breeding season typically of about 25 birds that also roost communally. They are particularly well-suited to consuming massive quantities of ticks, which might otherwise spread Lyme disease.

Woylies or brush-tailed bettongs are small, critically endangered, bipedal marsupials native to the shrubland of Australia. They mainly eat the fruiting bodies of underground fungi - not a problem for woylies as they are prodigious diggers. This woylie, appropriately named Truffles, is 7 months old.
The Northern Carmine bee-eater is a pure insect eater, it prefers bees, which it hunts in flight. They nest in holes and use their beak to dig out tunnels 1 to 2 m in length for this purpose.
Female dragonflies fake sudden death to avoid male advances.

Pairs and small groups of African Red-eyed Bulbuls forage in riverine thickets in the Karoo and in arid thorny woodland and scrub, eating a variety of fruit and invertebrates. The species has a typical bubbly musical bulbul song, slower than that of the similar-sounding Common Bulbul.

Emperor penguins have yellow ear patches that are "open" fading into the white of the breast feathers, whereas king penguins have orange ear patches that are "closed" by a band of black feathers. Emperor penguin chicks have distinctive plumage with a large white face patch.

The geoduck (pronounced gooey duck) is a very large saltwater clam native to coastal waters along the northeastern Pacific Ocean. It is known as a broadcast spawner - both males and females release billions of spermatozoa and eggs respectively into the sea to reproduce. This specimen was released.
Male northern elephant seal, Mirounga angustirostris, can memorize and recognize the rhythm of other seal’s voices, and use that rhythm to identify his male competitor.
Australian king parrots range from north and central Queensland to southern Victoria. They are frequently seen in small groups with various species of rosella.

The Hummingbird Bobtail Squid have bioluminescent bacteria within their bodies. These glowing bacteria are then used as camouflage by the bobtail squid to mimic the moonlight at night and to eliminate their own shadows, thereby protecting against predators

The ribbon eel is a species of moray eel whose coloration depends on developmental stage and gender. Juveniles are jet black with a yellow dorsal fin, adult females are yellow and blue, and adult males are blue to black in coloration. It can grow to 1.3 m (51 in) in length and live up to 20 years.
Stingrays date back on the fossil record to the Jurassic period, 150 million years ago.

The pyrrhuloxia (pronounced "peer-uh-LOX-ee-a"), also called the desert cardinal, is a song bird native to the southwestern US and northern Mexico. Although it bears a strong resemblance to the northern cardinal, the pyrrhuloxia is its own distinct species, however, they both share the same genus.

Glass sponges look more like delicate vases than animals. Their intricate structure manages water flow reducing drag. Some may live for tens of thousands of years limited only by sea level change. Over ~800 million years they've evolved some of the most complex medical molecules known to science.

The dogface pufferfish(Arothron nigropunctatus) may be adorable, but don't let those puppy dog eyes fool you. This puffer is laced with a toxin that’s 1.2k times more poisonous than cyanide. It often sports some dark shading around face, making it look like an underwater pup.

In parts of the black-capped chickadee's range with very cold winters, such as Minnesota, survival rates are affected by access to supplemental food. Chickadees with access to bird feeders are twice as likely to survive the winter than those without access to this supplemental food.
A new study which helped pet parrots make video calls to each other suggests that the birds may have benefited from making new feathered friends over the internet.

Eastern bluebirds are social, and will sometimes gather in flocks of over a hundred. However, they are territorial during the breeding season and may continue to defend a feeding area throughout the winter.

Seneca white deer, as they are locally called, live in 43 square km preserve, a former army depot, in Seneca County, NY. They are leucistic white-tailed deer, and their population consists of 700 members, approximately 300 of which are white, making it the largest herd of white deer in the world.

Acorn woodpeckers are so good at snugly fitting acorns into holes they make in trees that they often have trouble pulling them out. In fact, whenever the woodpecker finds a loose acorn in a hole, it will put the acorn into a tighter fitting hole. It's all about keeping critters from stealing them.

Ducks like Millie have extreme mechano-sensitive neurons in their bills. The neurons they have actually display a much stronger response to a light touch than the corresponding neurons in most other birds and mammals would.
Marmots are ambiverts that love their burrows but also social activities. They spend 6-8 months in hibernation, which holds the key to their longevity (and perhaps human space travel)

The Javan Rhino: A derpy, cute, rhinoceros that is sadly in declining numbers, and only about 80 are alive right now. Just to put in perspective how endangered they are, every pixel of this image represents one single Javan Rhino in the world.

Royal spoonbills, native to Oceania, inhabit wetlands feeding on crustaceans, fish and small insects as they sweep their bills from side to side. When they are breeding, long white plumes grow from the back of the head and colored patches appear on the face. Clutch sizes are usually 2 to 3 eggs.

The plains viscacha lives in a communal burrow system—called a viscachera—as part of a colony that can number in the hundreds. Some have been known to exist for centuries. Those near human settlements often horde man-made objects, like brooms and tables, to cover the entrances of their burrows.

This iridescent bug is the cuckoo wasp, belonging to the family Chrysididae. Its glittering appearance is imparted by the many tiny, deep pits on its body surface.This wasp exhibits similar kleptoparasitic behavior as the cuckoo bird, laying its eggs in the nests of other wasps & stealing their food

The Canadian Lynx is medium sized cat (family Felidae) that lives in Canada and the Northern USA (including Alaska). They have long legs and large broad paws that are covered in fur. This allows them to move quickly on snow.

Peacock spiders are native to Australia (with the exception of Maratus furvus, which is found in China). A species of jumping spider, they can jump up to 40 times their body length, and males are known for their brightly rainbow-colored bodies and ability to dance during their courtship rituals.

Vampire Moths (Genus Calyptra): the vampire moth has a specialized proboscis that it generally uses to pierce/feed on fruit, but some have also been observed using the same tactic to feed on the blood of mammals, including humans

The magnificent frigate bird will harass other birds midair until their victims regurgitate their recently eaten food, which the frigatebird steals and consumes. This behaviour has landed it the nicknames of "man-o-war bird" and "pirate bird".

The brown thrasher utilizes its vision while scouring for food. It usually forages for food under leaves, brushes, and soil debris on the ground using its bill. It then swipes the floor in side-to-side motions, and investigates the area it recently foraged in.

The Sumatran rhino is the smallest and the hairiest rhino species on Earth. It loves to wallow in mud baths during the day; bathing in mud for up to 300 minutes a day. Its body hair helps the mud adhere to its skin, keeping its body cool and preventing its skin from drying.

The slow loris is the only known venomous primate. When threatened, it lifts its arm over its head to lick glands close to its armpits which secret a noxious oil. The mix of saliva and oil produces a venomous solution, giving them a bite that can cause anaphylactic shock and death in humans.

The Pallas's cat lives in mountainous areas and has a stocky, thick-coated body to protect it from the cold. This feline's expressive face has round pupils rather than the slits that most small cats have. It is known to be grouchy - a kitten will growl before even being able to open its eyes.

The blue button jellyfish gets its name from its blue coat button-shaped body and jellyfish-like tentacles, but it's not a jellyfish at all. It's a marine organism composed of colonies of hydrozoan polyps and is more closely related to the Portuguese man o' war. Its sting can cause mild irritation.

The red-tailed comet (Sappho sparganurus) is a hummingbird native to Bolivia, Argentina, Chile and Peru. The male has an iridescent, golden-reddish forked tail, longer than the length of its body. This red-tailed comet stops by the home of someone watering their flowers with a hose and takes a bath.

Male giraffes' spots are more strongly correlated with their social behavior than with their age, according to research that was published in the journal Animal Behaviour. Per study, that the darker-colored male giraffes tend to be more solitary & dominant than their lighter-colored counterparts

The serval has the longest legs and largest ears of any cat relative to its body size. Its rather elongated neck gives it the nickname "giraffe cat." Native to Africa, the serval's closest relatives are the African golden cat and the caracal, all of which can jump quite high to catch overhead prey.
Born live, young monkey-tailed skinks, native to the Solomon Islands, stay with and are protected by both their parents for as long as a year before leaving their social group.

Polar bears are technically marine mammals, spending much of their year at sea. Their fur actually has no white pigment, their hairs are hollow and reflect light, allowing them to look white and blend in against the snow. Underneath, they have black skin to easier absorb heat from the sun.

The songs of goldcrests vary only slightly across their range and consist of a single song type, but much more divergence has occurred in the isolated Macaronesian populations. There are variations between islands and within an island, but individual males on the Azores can have up to 3 song types.

Barn Swallows have a long, deeply forked tail that streams out behind this agile flyer and sets it apart from all other North American swallows. True to their name, they build their cup-shaped mud nests almost exclusively on human-made structures.

Polar bears primarily eat seals. Polar bears often rest silently at a seal's breathing hole in the ice, waiting for a seal in the water to surface. A polar bear may also hunt by swimming beneath the ice. Polar bears roam the Arctic ice sheets and swim in that region's coastal waters.

Although Northern Flickers eat fruits, berries, seeds, and nuts, their primary food is insects. Ants alone can make up 45% of their diet. Other invertebrates eaten include flies, butterflies, moths, beetles, and snails.

The strawberry squid gets its name from its sparkling red body dotted by tiny bioluminescent photophores. It spends daytime hiding from predators in the dark ocean depths and comes closer to the surface at night, feeling safer under cover of darkness, to feed on fish, crustaceans and smaller squid.
The red wolf (Canis rufus) is one of the world's most endangered canids, native to the southeastern United States. It is monogamous, with both parents participating in the rearing of young.

The golden snub-nosed monkey roams the high mountainous forests of western-central China. It's able to survive below-freezing temperatures by sleeping clustered together, in the lower forest canopy, with others in its group. During barren winter months, it will survive by eating mostly lichen.
The average adult cow , like Colin, weighs about 1,200 pounds; in one day it can eat more than 20 pounds of grass and drink up to 30 gallons of water.

Piping plovers (threatened federally and endangered in many states) nest on beaches from NC to Canada during the busy beachgoing season. For the chicks to survive until they can fly, the parents must lead them from the dunes to the water and back to feed. Be on the lookout if you go sunbathing!
At 30 years old, a Portuguese dog named Bobi set a new world record on February 1st of this year for being the world’s oldest dog ever, a record previously unbroken since 1910.

Native brown bears had once roamed about Switzerland until the early 1900's and then disappeared. They have since been re-introduced to nearby forests in northern Italy. Several brown bears have made their way to the Parc Naziunal Svizzer. This brown bear mom in Bärenpark Bern is ready to head home.

A pennant-winged nightjar male is distinguished by a long ninth pair of primary feathers and white bands over his wings. The long 'pennant' feathers are grown during the breeding season—getting longer every year, becoming twice the bird's body length—and are easily dropped after breeding.

Happy World Bee Day! Unlike honeybees, mason bees (Osmia spp) do not have pollen baskets on their legs. They carry pollen on their abdomen. Belly flopping onto flowers is a very efficient way to collect pollen for their offspring.

Colonies of crested auklets, very gregarious seabirds, can often be smelled before they are seen; apparently giving off an intense citrus smell akin to that of tangerines. The stronger a bird smells, the more successful it appears to be at finding a mate.

The Luzon Bleeding-Heart, named for their distinctive red plumage extending towards their belly. Native to the island of Luzon in the Philippines, they are also shy, secretive, and quiet often staying close to the ground except for nesting.

There was a 25% increase in the population of the bulky flightless kākāpō parrot of New Zealand in the last year. The total is now 252 birds whilst in 2002 there were only 86. With the help of the Ngai Tahu Maori tribe there was a good breeding season and several AI attempts were successful.

Bolas spiders are orb-weavers which have adapted to throw their webs at prey rather than wait passively for prey to fly into a trap. Some species produce chemicals which mimic the pheromones of moths to lure in their prey.

Reindeer have a formidable defense strategy when faced with a perceived threat. They will sometimes form "cyclones" as the herd begins walking together in a tight-knit circular fashion to deter any predator that may come near. This behavior is also practiced by reindeer kept in corrals.
Emperor penguins can survive temperatures down to -50 Celsius or -58 Fahrenheit by shuffling around in tight packs of up to 5000 adults and chicks. (Source- World Wildlife Fund)
The World's Largest/Oldest Lake,(Lake Baikal), is also home to the only Fully Freshwater species of Seal.

The European hamster (Cricetus cricetus), also known as the Eurasian hamster, or common hamster, is the only species of hamster in the genus Cricetus. It is native to grassland and similar habitats in a large part of Eurasia, extending from Belgium to the Altai mountains and Yenisey River in Russia.

Closing out on the Year of the Tiger. The Siberian Tiger is native to Russia, China, and possibly North Korea. They commonly eat wild boar and deer but have, on occasion, successfully hunted bears. At one point, it was believed that the total population was less than 400 tigers in the wild.

The Cockchafer Beetle: these beetles use chemosensory organs on their antennae to detect the sex pheromones released by potential mates; when the prongs on their antennae are fanned out, it often indicates that they are actively searching for a mate

The Fossa, Cryptoprocta Ferox, Is Madagascar's Largest Native Carnivore, Able To Kill The Largest Lemur Species. Today, They Are Classified As A Vulnerable Species With Only About 2,500 In The Wild (Photo Credit: Sachin Rai - Instagram)

Despite its derpy appearance, Bruno's casque-headed frog (Nyctimantis brunoi) is no joke. Endemic to Brazil, their venom - 25 times more potent than native pit vipers - is delivered via headbutt using tiny bony spines on their skull.

Common Grackles are blackbirds that look like they've been slightly stretched. They're taller and longer tailed than a typical blackbird, with a longer, more tapered bill and glossy-iridescent bodies.

The Cape sugarbird is a specialist nectar feeder when it comes to feeding off Proteaceae. Its long, sharp beak is used to reach the nectar of a variety of species of protea with its long brush-tipped tongue.

The indigo bunting migrates at night—navigating by starlight—flying up to 2000 miles (3,200 km) between breeding and wintering grounds. It appears to have an internal clock that allows it to adjust its flight path in orientation with the stars, even as they move.
This is the wolly armadillo, dasypus pilosus. It lives in a very small region in peru and close to nothing is know about it's behavior or population in the wild.

The Shellback Crab (Genus Hypoconcha): these crabs create their own makeshift shields out of clamshells; the crab has a semi-membranous body that can be pressed into the contours of the shell, producing a suction mechanism which then holds the shell firmly in place

The English Lop is a large breed of domestic rabbits developed in 19th Century England. They have longest ears of any rabbit breed. However the long ears can cause problems, such an increased tendency for frostbite and ear infections, as well as restriction in mobility leading to obesity.

The rough-skinned newt (Taricha granulosa) is highly toxic. It produces tetrodotoxin, similar to some pufferfish, which blocks sodium ion channels in cells. Only a few snake species are resistant to its poison.

The Himalayan monal lives at high altitudes—up to 4,500 metres (14,800 ft)—in the hill forests and shrublands of the Himalayan mountains. The males of this species are some of the most colourful birds in the world, displaying an entire rainbow of iridescent feathers.
Baby Olive Ridley sea turtle makes a break for it. They are the smallest of the sea turtles and are endangered due to disappearance of their nesting sites.

The hairy long-nosed armadillo, native to Peru, has a distinctive coat of long brown fur which grows through tiny pores in its armor. It can weigh up to 5 kg (10.4 lb) and grow to 58 cm (23 in) long, including the tail. It is estimated that there are only 12 known individuals in its wild population.
While barred owls are originally birds of the eastern United States, they spread through the Pacific Northwest and California over the twentieth century [OC]

The Mexican alligator lizard is plated in armour-like scales that can range in colour from a vibrant emerald green to a deep teal blue. White or yellow patches encircle its eyes, making its stare appear observant and alert.

Pigeons are one of just 3 types of birds that produce crop milk, a secretion made from food that the parent birds eat. Crop milk is produced and stored in a pouch in their throats, then regurgitated into the chicks throat. Both male and female pigeons are involved in feeding their newborn chicks.

Though not quite as social as their close cousin, the grey wolf, coyotes are known to form lifelong bonds with their partners and parents. Both the mother and father will work round the clock to feed and protect their pups, and are sometimes assisted by their older offspring who haven’t dispersed.

Takins travel through bamboo forests and mountains in Asia to elevations of 4,300 metres (14,000 feet). Seeking out their favourite feeding grounds and salt licks, herds will follow the same routes yearly, creating a network of long-used paths. They are slow-moving animals, but skilled climbers.

The Northern Flicker is one of the few North American woodpeckers that is strongly migratory. Flickers in the northern parts of their range move south for the winter, although a few individuals often stay rather far north.

When Europeans colonised Australia they brought cattle that made wet cowpats. They didn't know that native dung beetles were mostly unable to process them having evolved with dry marsupial poo. Millions of flies swarmed for 200y until funding arrived to import scarab beetles able to bury cowpats.

Queen Anne's lace often attracts ants! Partly because the plant also attracts aphids which ants farm, but also because the flowers are so shallow the nectar at their base is easy to reach, even for little ant mouths.

Caecilians are wormlike, burrowing amphibians with smooth, moist skin which appears narrowly segmented. Their eyes are small and covered with skin, visual perception being limited to determining between light and dark. This yellow-striped caecilian was found by a gardener in Thailand and released.

Jumping spiders (Family:Salticidae) can take down prey many times their size. These spiders have elaborate courtship dances where the male eventually passes the female a packet of reproductive material with a quick tap. Longer contact could be dangerous! The peacock spider is particularly showy.
The honey possum or noolbenger (Tarsipes rostratus) is the only entirely nectarivorous mammal which is not a bat.
Pigs, like Amelia and Curly, are able to recognize familiar over unfamiliar conspecifics, which allows them to form and maintain stable social groups.

The hog badger is a shy and elusive southern Asian animal, that generally resembles a European badger, apart from its larger claws and elongated pig-like snout. It uses its maneuverable snout to turn over dirt when foraging, like a pig does, giving it its common name.

Paedophryne amauensis is a New Guinean Frog that is the smallest vertebrate known so far at only 0.77 cm/0.3 inches long! They do not have a tadpole stage. Instead the babies hatch out as miniature versions of the adults.
With little to no fear of man, the Giant Seychelles Tortoise was hunted to near extinction in 1840. They were rediscovered and protected. Also, they love head scratches.

Hutias are fairly large rodents that inhabit the islands of the Caribbean, and they resemble nutrias (coypus) to some degree. Depending on the species, they can weigh from 2 to 8.5 kg (4.4 - 18.7 lbs). This is first time video footage of hutias in Cuba as they feed around coastal limestone caves.

The great eared nightjar is a species of nightjar in the family Caprimulgidae. It is found in southwest India and in parts of Southeast Asia. This very large nightjar has long barred wings, a barred tail and long ear-tufts which are often recumbent

The Iberian ribbed newt or gallipato, native to the Iberian Peninsula and Morocco, is the largest European newt species. It is known for its sharp ribs which can puncture through its sides. This defense mechanism, which can sting a predator, causes little harm to the newt.
The cornual branches of the lachrymal and infratrochlear nerves provide sensory stimulation to the horns of goats, like Benny

The golden-fronted woodpecker's diet is adult and larval arthropods, some aerial insects, much fruit and nuts, and corn. It has been observed predating other birds' eggs. The species forages mainly in trees, especially on major limbs and typically below 6 m (20 ft).

American Oystercatcher courtship in spring is boisterous, with courting birds pacing quickly over the sand in unison, giving a piping call that increases in tempo, and pivoting in arcing patterns around the beach. One pair often attracts neighboring pairs to begin this display in a 'Piping Ceremony'

Sandhill cranes are mainly herbivorous, but eat various types of food, depending on availability. They often feed with their bills down to the ground as they root around for seeds and other foods, in shallow wetlands with vegetation or various upland habitats.

With horn-like projections of varying lengths, there’s no mistaking the dragon headed caterpillar. Found in temperate regions across nearly every continent, 400 species have so far been discovered. They belong to the leafwing butterfly subfamily Charaxina.

The northern cardinal is a mid-sized songbird with a body length of 21–23 cm (8.3–9.1 in). It has a distinctive crest on the head and a mask on the face which is black in the male and gray in the female. The male is a vibrant red, while the female is a reddish olive color.

The little skate (Leucoraja erinacea) is found along the Atlantic Ocean from Nova Scotia to North Carolina where it mainly lives in sandy or gravelly areas feeding on crustaceans and amphipods. Females produce a total of 10-35 eggs annually. Here is a baby skate hatching out of its egg case.
The blue-streaked lory (Eos reticulata) is also known as the blue-necked lory. It is a medium-sized parrot (31 cm), which is found on the Tanimbar Islands and Babar in the southern Moluccas.

Baltimore orioles forage in trees and shrubs, also making short flights to catch insects. They acrobatically clamber, hover and hang among foliage as they comb high branches. They mainly eat insects, berries and nectar, and are often seen sipping at hummingbird feeders.

Endangered male northern quolls are giving up sleep in favour of having more sex – and it could be killing them, according to a study that investigated why male northern quolls usually mate themselves to death in one season while females can live and reproduce for up to four years.

The Baird’s Tapir is the largest native land mammal in central and South America, weighing up to 660 lbs (300 kg). Despite their hippo-like body and elephant-like nose, they are closest related to horses and rhinoceroses.
While the adult stage of Bee Flies (Bombuliidae) are pollinators, the larval stages are generally parasitic. It is quite the metamorphosis!

Maleos are communal nesters with a unique reproductive strategy. Native to the Sulawesi, maleos dig deep holes and lay their eggs inside, covering them with sand and plant material. Solar and geothermal heat incubate the eggs. When the single egg per nest hatches, the chick digs out and flies off.

Insectivorous marsupials native to Australia and New Guinea, striped possums have elongated and highly sensitive 4th fingers. Rapidly tapping the side of a tree, they listen for wood-boring insects. They then chew a hole in the bark and extract the insects with their specialized fingers.

This is a Southern blue-ringed octopus. They are found in tidal rock pools along the south coast of Australia. They are venomous with venom that can kill humans. They eat lobsters, crabs, shrimp, and shellfish. There average lifespan is only about seven months. The females die after her eggs hatch.
Barn owls are incredibly efficient hunters, a family of owls can eat upwards of 4,000 mice each year [OC]

The Egyptian vulture is a rare example of a tool-using bird. It will fly great distances to find a satisfactory rock, which it then uses to break open large eggs by repeatedly dropping the rock onto the egg until it cracks. It learns this clever trick by watching other Egyptian vultures.

The rosy-faced lovebird inhabits dry, open country in southwest Africa. Its range extends from southwest Angola across most of Namibia to the lower Orange River valley in northwest South Africa. It lives up to 1,600 metres above sea level in broad-leaved woodland, semi-desert, and mountainous areas.

Helmeted guineafowl are terrestrial birds, and prone to run rather than fly when alarmed. Like most gallinaceous birds, they have a short-lived, explosive flight and rely on gliding to cover extended distances. They can walk 6,2 miles (10 km) and more in a day.

Like their relatives, the sea horses, the male Weedy sea dragons brood the eggs. The brood patch is made of tiny cups of blood-rich tissue, and each cup holds and nourishes one egg. After eight weeks, the eggs hatch over a period of a couple days.

The Oilbird is unique among birds since it is the only nocturnal fruit-eating(oil palm) bird that navigates via echolocation. Its eyes, w/c have the max capability for light gathering of any terrestrial vertebrate,have 1M rod cells/mm2 in its retina, are another adaptation for its nighttime foraging

Sloth Bears carry their young on their back for the first 7 to 9 months of their lives, and are the only bear species which regularly transports their cubs on their backs. (Photo Credit: Chetan Aand - Instagram)

Northern cardinals are preyed upon by a wide variety of predators native to North America, including falcons, all Accipiter hawks, shrikes, bald eagles, golden eagles and several owls, including long-eared owls, and eastern screech owls.

Red squirrels Excess food is put into caches - buried or in nooks or holes in trees, and eaten when food is scarce. Although the red squirrel remembers where it created caches at a better-than-chance level, its spatial memory is substantially less accurate and durable than that of grey squirrels.

The American white ibis is territorial, defending the nesting and display sites against intruders. Agonistic or threat displays include lunging forward with the bill in a horizontal posture, and standing upright and snapping the bill opposite another bird engaging in the same display.

Hamerkops are compulsive nest builders. A pair of these birds will build huge nests, measuring over 1.5 m (4 ft 11 in) across. One nest can take up to 14 weeks to build, and they usually build 3 - 5 yearly, whether they are breeding or not. An estimated 8,000 sticks are used to build a nest.

Like many other unpalatable insects, Bombardier Beetles harness the power of chemicals for defense. Unlike other toxic insects, the chemical defense for these beetles is a violent exothermic reaction which can scald potential threats.

Jacana males are responsible for raising the chicks, and they will quickly collect the chicks under their wings at the slightest indication of danger. When it's safe, the chicks are let out again. This bronze-winged jacana dad gestures to his chicks that the coast is clear and it's safe to feed.

Are roosters similar to dinosaurs? A rare, mummified specimen of the duck-billed dinosaur Edmontosauraus regalis shows for the first time in 2013 that those dinosaurs' heads were adorned with a fleshy comb, most similar to the roosters' red crest.

Echidnas have a number of tricks that seem to allow them to survive in higher than expected temperatures. They blow bubbles onto their beaks which take heat away from their blood by evaporation. They also raise their hollow spines exposing skin to reduce their insulation effect. (Links in comments)
Honeybees (Apis mellifera) were introduced to North America for agriculture and can compete for resources with native bees like this mason bee.

Sea otters form groups called "rafts", typically of between 10 and 100 individuals. When they rest or sleep, they will wrap themselves, and their pups, in kelp to stop them from drifting out to sea or hold paws to stay together. They live and feed along the coast, rarely, if ever, coming ashore.

Adult Lesser Hedgehog Tenrecs weigh about 7 ounces (200g). They look similar to hedgehogs as a result of convergent evolution. Their common ancestors diverged around 20-40 million years ago. All tenrecs have a cloaca, meaning they poo and pee from the same hole like birds and reptiles.
Calliope hummingbirds are the smallest birds in the US, weighting only 2-3 grams! They feed on nectar and help pollinate many species of flowering plants [OC]

The marbled polecat is a small mustelid that lives in deserts and dry steppes throughout southeastern Europe, Russia, and China. It is the only living member of the genus Vormela, from the German word "Würmlein", which means—appropriately for this animal's lanky body—"little worm".

The California sea lion is one of six species of sea lion, and it is listed as 'least concern' in terms of their population status. During the breeding season, adult male sea lions tend to establish and maintain territorial boundaries, and they will chase off other male sea lions that intrude.

Acorn woodpeckers, as their name implies, depend heavily on acorns for food. Acorns are such an important resource to the California populations that acorn woodpeckers may nest in the fall to take advantage of the fall acorn crop, a rare behavior in birds.

Norway rats (Rattus norvegicus) and Roof Rats (Rattus rattus) are two closely related species of rat. Norway rats are fossorial, so they evolved to live in burrows. Roof Rats are arboreal so they evolved to live in trees, their paws and legs are adapted to climbing and jumping.

Black-capped Chickadees are northern forest birds that range throughout most of Canada and up to Alaska. These non-migratory birds stay within their home territory into the cold, snowy winter. They like eating seeds in winter and insects in summer, and mate for life.

When ducklings are born, they rely on one another and their mother to huddle and stay warm until their feathers grow. However, once they have feathers, they are much more capable of regulating their body temperature. Here are our ducklings in a warming cuddle puddle 🥰

The American goldfinch is a granivore and adapted for the consumption of seedheads, with a conical beak to remove the seeds and agile feet to grip the stems of seedheads while feeding. It is a social bird and will gather in large flocks while feeding and migrating.
Chillingham cattle are the only breed of wild cattle in the world. They have been around for over 700 years.

Mountain pygmy possums are critically endangered, nocturnal, alpine, hibernating marsupials. Kids in NSW have been baking Bogon Bikkies with the same nutritional value as the Bogon Moths that the tiny possums eat. The moths are missing because of intense fires and habitat loss. Links in comments.

This is Siberian crane,there are 3200-4000 of them.what makes it unique about it,its serrated bill, enables it to easily feed on underground roots.this bird in this image called omid, the only Siberian crane in iran.people called him omid(believe) bc they believe him coming with a family one day

The Goat Moth larvae (Cossus cossus) get their name because of their goat-like smell. They have been regarded as pests as they are able to kill trees, living and feeding in them for 5 years before they turn into moths.

The moray eel has a second set of jaws - called the 'pharyngeal jaws' - located behind its skull. These jaws are able to shoot forward almost the entire length of the skull, to snatch up prey and deliver it to the eel's esophagus for swallowing.
Rabbits have hinged skulls to help absorb shock when they jump and sprint. It minimizes damage to the brain due to impact but also keeps their vision steady when running!

The lowland streaked tenrec is the only mammal known to communicate using stridulation. It vibrates specialized spines against each other to produce a high frequency sound, a communication method more commonly seen in insects such as crickets.
After the second World War, there was just about 50 English Longhorn cattle remaining. Today, there are over 12,000 of them!

The kitti's hog-nosed bat (Craseonycteris thonglongyai), also known as the bumblebee bat, is a near-threatened species of bat. It occurs in western Thailand and southeast Myanmar, where it occupies limestone caves along rivers. It's arguably the world's smallest mammal.
Many bat species have a nose leaf. These structures help to focus echolocation calls.

Radiated tortoises have yellow lines radiating from the center of the shell plate, hence its name. Those rare tortoises are critically endangered due to habitat loss and poach. Here are two baby tortoises hatched in Chester Zoo.

Giant pandas can’t process plant tissue particularly well, but they do have some evolutionary tricks to make it easier for themselves. One of my favorites is that giant pandas can metabolize and detoxify cyanide, which is naturally present in the bamboo they eat.

The waved albatross is the largest bird in Galapagos with a wingspan up to 8 feet (around 2.5 m). It gets its name from the wave like patterns on the adults’ wings. This frontal view shows its distinctive "eyebrows" and jet-black eyes.

Sweat Bees (Family: Halictidae) are named for their habit of drinking sweat. Their sting has been described as "light, ephemeral, almost fruity. A tiny spark has singed a single hair on your arm." This one has a penchant for pollen.

Agoutis are rodents found in forested areas in Central and South America. When eating, agoutis sit on their hind legs and hold food between their fore paws. This male agouti was rehabilitated at a rescue center in Costa Rica and released, however, it seems he doesn't have any plans to skedaddle.

A genet is a small viverrid of the genus Genetta, which consists of 17 species of small African carnivorans. The common genet is the only genet present in Europe and occurs in the Iberian Peninsula, Italy and France. They are opportunistic omnivores that also feed on plants and fruit.

Snowy owls are the largest bird species in the arctic, 63 to 73 cm long with an average wingspan of 170 cm. Females are larger and heavier than the males, weighing 1550 to 1600 grams, compared to males which weigh 1450 to 1500 grams.

The Hummingbird Hawk Moth: often mistaken for a hummingbird, this moth has a wing-speed of up to 85 beats per second, and like a hummingbird, it rotates its wings in a figure-8 motion that enables it to hover in mid-air; it also feeds on the nectar from flowers and emits a humming noise as it flies

Unlike other hyenas, the aardwolf is an insectivore; the majority of its diet consists of termites. It will use its broad, sticky tongue to catch hundreds of thousands of termites. While aardvarks destroy termite mounds, the aardwolf doesn't, leaving it with a constant supply of food.

The Galápagos tortoise is one of the longest living vertebrates, with one in captivity reaching 177 years old. Owing to their slow growth rate and late sexual maturity, they are particularly vulnerable to extinction without conservation efforts. This melanistic tortoise lives at a Florida sanctuary.
Southern three-banded armadillos are the only species of armadillo that can curl up into a ball

California scrub jays, like many other corvids, exploit ephemeral surpluses by storing food in scattered caches within their territories. They rely on highly accurate and complex memories to recover the hidden caches, often after long periods of time.

Koalas eat eucalyptus leaves, which contain many toxic compounds similar to cyanide. "Koalas can sleep for up to 20 hours a day, due to their low energy diet, and the intense amount of energy required to break down toxic leaves."

Greater Gliders are velvety-furred marsupials w/ distinctive large fluffy ears, the largest in the ringtail possum fam,can glide up to 100m at a time.W/ a highly specialized diet feeding almost exclusively on eucalypt leaves & using 2-18 tree hollows for shelter. Listed as endangered species in 2022

The endangered Big-headed African mole-rat lives on Ethiopia's Bale Mountains, and is the primary prey of the also endangered Ethiopian wolf. They are extremely cautious while foraging and building new tunnels, equipped with large incisors for added defense.

Southern viscachas are colonial animals that live in groups. They do not hibernate and are mostly active soon after dawn and in the evening. Part of their day is spent perched on a rock sunbathing, grooming, or resting. It was not dawn but I was lucky to meet one in Bolivian wilderness. So cute 🥰

The shiny cowbird is a year-round resident across most of South America, where it lives in open areas such as open forests and cultivated land. Within the last century, the range of the species has shifted northward, and birds have been recorded in the West Indies and southern Florida.

The long-tailed tit is insectivorous throughout the year. It eats predominantly arthropods, preferring the eggs and larvae of moths and butterflies. Occasional vegetable matter (such as seeds) is taken in the autumn.

There are approximately 20 extant species of armadillo, and all of them originated in South America. Two species, the northern naked-tailed armadillo and nine-banded armadillo, are found in Central America, the latter of which has also reached the US. ZeFrank provides the narration for this video.

Macrocephalon maleo, a critically endangered bird, bury their eggs in hot sand, use the solar energy and geotherm to incubate them. Chicks have well developed feathers, so they can fly immediately after hatching.

Crested barbets are found singly or in pairs. They like to bounce around on the ground looking for food, they usually call from a branch out in the open. They do not fly easily and then only for short distances.
Not all Cuckoos are parasitic, Green-Billed Cuckoos will build their own nests to raise their children.

The yellow-throated warbler is a woodland species with a preference for coniferous or swamp tree species, in which it preferably nests. They are insectivorous, but will include a considerable amount of berries and nectar in their diet outside the breeding season

Martens are usually seen to be solitary, but the yellow-throated marten, Martes flavigula, can hunt in pairs, or even in packs of three or more. In 2017, India, three yellow-throated martens was witnessed cooperating hunt a macaque.

Orcas have strong family bonds that transcend multiple generations, lead by the oldest female the pods are set to remain together for life. Even the males remain beside their families for their entire lives, this makes every member of the group important and the risk of losing a member very serious.
When a herd of gaur cows perceived predator, they will gathering together, facing outward, kicking their hind legs and tossing their horns, in order to protect their calves from tiger or leopard.

A marten is a weasel-like mammal in the genus Martes within the subfamily Guloninae, in the family Mustelidae. They have bushy tails and large paws with partially retractile claws. The fur varies from yellowish to dark brown, depending on the species

Caribou have hollow hairs that not only serve as crucial insulation during the winter time but also provide buoyancy while swimming. Caribou are excellent swimmers, and they will often swim during their migrations or when exploring new feeding areas. These caribou are crossing a lake in Alaska.

Dugongs are known to have symbiotic relationships with remoras. Remoras will eat the parasites they find on the dugongs' skin. In return, the dugongs provide remoras with protection from larger predators. Dugongs also help seagrass meadows stay healthy by leaving the roots intact as they forage.
Elephant shrews live in forests and plains in six African countries, eat insects, and give birth to young three to five times a year.

Grote's Bertholdia Moth: when predatory bats are detected nearby, these moths begin to emit a rapid series of ultrasonic clicks that act as a "jammer," interfering with the bat's sonar signals and enabling the moth to avoid detection
The penis of the Dark-winged Lesser House Bat (Scotoecus hirundo) can measure >25% of their body length.

Kittens are born with blue eyes, which may change color as they age. An association with blue eyes and deafness has long been established. Charles Darwin suggested that the poor-hearing of newborn kittens was linked to their blue eyes.

Curve-billed thrashers share a very similar range to the cactus wren, as well as a favorite species to nest in: the jumping cholla. Because of this, interspecific conflict is frequent. Fights over food are rare, but fights to protect fledglings are heated.

Venus girdles (Cestida) are an unusual order of ribbon-shaped comb jellies with only two recognized species. Like other comb jellies, they swim with thousands of tiny hairs called cilia, which refract light as they beat back and forth, producing a rainbow effect when a light is shone on them.

Mountain Chickadee's diet is insects during the summer and breeding season; conifer seeds and other plant seeds are taken throughout the year. They cling to the undersides of branches and to tree trunks, searching for food in the bark or breaking seeds open by hammering them with their beaks.
These are Tardigrades, they are microscopic eight-legged animals that have been to outer space and would likely survive the apocalypse. They also look like little bears, hence the name; Water Bear.
Dormouse - an Eurasian rodent best know for hibernating up to 7 months. Genetically close to a squirrel, they sleep in tree holes left by woodpeckers.
This barred owl is "anting." Owls find a colony of ants and let them clean the owl's feathers and skin, a perfect symbiotic relationship (that is very cool to watch).

The red-winged blackbird is omnivorous. It feeds primarily on plant materials, including seeds from weeds and waste grain such as corn and rice, but about a quarter of its diet consists of insects and other small animals, and considerably more so during breeding season.
The Red-shanked Douc (Pygathrix nemaeus) are colorful monkeys with moderate sexual dimorphism. The young are slightly lighter in color until they reach about 10 months of age.

The Dark-eyed Junco forages on the ground. In winter, they often forage in flocks that may contain several subspecies. They mainly eat seeds, supplemented by the occasional insect. A flock of dark-eyed juncos has been known to be called a blizzard.

Presenting southern rockhoppers. They are among the world's smallest penguins, standing about 20 inches. During annual breeding times, rockhoppers gather in vast, noisy colonies, often numbering in the hundreds of thousands.

All pangolins are covered in scales made of keratin—the same material as human fingernails—which gives them the nickname "scaly anteater." The pangolin’s armor is so tough that even predators such as lions can’t bite through it.

House finches forage on the ground or in vegetation normally. They primarily eat grains, seeds and berries, being voracious consumers of weed seeds such as nettle and dandelion; included are incidental small insects such as aphids.

Isopods first appeared in the fossil record 300 million years ago, and today there are more than 10,000 species, both terrestrial and aquatic. All have rigid, segmented exoskeletons and two pairs of antennae. While this isopod is resting on the ocean floor, a deep-sea skate appears to befriend it.

The plant Veratrum californicum, California false hellebore, has a chemical, Cyclopamine, that can induce cyclopia, being born with a single eye, in lambs whose mother eats it during pregnancy. Cyclopamine inhibits signaling in the sonic hedgehog pathway.

Bumblebees can learn by example: Researchers created a test where bees could access sugar water if they pulled on a string. 60% of bumblebees that watched another bee pull the string figured out they could do it too.
Klipspringer mates for life, and the partners generally never stray more than 5m from each other. Each keeping lookout while the other grazes.

The Wavy-Lined Emerald Moth Caterpillar: these caterpillars are able to fashion their own camouflage by collecting flower petals and other bits of vegetation, then using silk to "glue" the pieces onto their bodies

The American yellow warbler (Setophaga petechia). Yellow warblers are the most widespread species in the diverse genus Setophaga. The species can be found throughout most of North America and migrates to wintering grounds from southern California to the Amazon region, Bolivia, and Peru.

The indigo bunting forages for food on the ground or in trees or shrubs. In winter, it often feeds in flocks , but is a solitary feeder during the breeding season, when the species eats insects, seeds and berries, including caterpillars, grasshoppers, spiders, beetles and grass seeds.

This Pacific Seahorse are the largest of their species, which can reach up to 14in long. They feed on organisms such as mysids, small crustaceans and other plankton. Camouflage helps the seahorse avoid predators, such as crabs, sea urchins, rays, fish. They have a life span of 3-5 years.
The bat-eared fox is a species of fox found on the African savanna. Its large ears, which have a role in thermoregulation.
Did you know that honey is basically 'puke' of bees? They digest the nectar they eat, and spit it back out in the honeycomb together with enzymes and bacteria, which helps it thicken and ripen

The Red-bellied Woodpecker uses its bill as a chisel, drilling into bark or probing cracks on trunk of trees. In this manner, it is able to pull out beetles and other insects from the tree with the help of its long tongue.
This is a Giant Ostracod/Seed Shrimp. They’re deep sea, gigantic versions of crustaceans that are usually as small as 0.2 mm.

Bohemian Waxwings primarily eat sweet fruits but supplement their diet w/insects. It favors juniper &rowan, w/c it eats either in pieces or whole. Waxwings have a large liver that helps convert sugar into energy.It can also metabolize alcohol produced by fermenting fruit,but it can still get drunk.

The earless monitor lizard is endemic to the island of Borneo and is exceedingly rare. While not displaying an ear opening or any other external ear structure, it is still capable of hearing. Its body is covered in six rows of very keeled scales.

The Red-Bellied Woodpecker uses its bill as a chisel, drilling into bark or probing cracks on trunk of trees. In this manner, it is able to pull out beetles and other insects from the tree with the help of its long tongue.
Dolphin's only allow half of their brains to sleep at a time, in order to stay alert and continue to breathe!

Tree-kangaroos are marsupials of the genus Dendrolagus, adapted for arboreal locomotion. They inhabit the tropical rainforests of New Guinea and far northeastern Queensland, along with some of the islands in the region. All tree-kangaroos are considered threatened due to hunting,habitat destruction.
4 eye fish have the ability to see both above and below the water at the same time, thanks to their two pupils and corneas per eye
White throated monitors can count till 6, this is significantly further than the average dog.
Kerry cattle are one of the oldest breeds of cattle. They are thought to have been bred for dairy for over 4000 years!
American pika, Ochotona princeps, is coprophagic – that means it eat its own feces, a study shows, pika’s caecal pellets is nutritious, they have higher nitrogen than plants pika usually eat

Luidia sarsii is a species of starfish that lives in deep cold waters off the coast of Europe. The fertilized eggs of these starfish develop into free-swimming juveniles conjoined with tail-like larval bodies (bipinnaria stage). Upon metamorphosis, the larval bodies detach from the young starfish.

Asian paradise flycatchers are monogamous and both parents contribute to nest building, brooding, and nestling care. The exaggerated tail feathers of males is likely present due to sexual selection. This tail does not seem to increase fitness in any other way.

Baltimore orioles forage in trees and shrubs, also making short flights to catch insects. They acrobatically clamber, hover and hang among foliage as they comb high branches. They mainly eat insects, berries and nectar, and are often seen sipping at hummingbird feeders.

Sand dollars are flat sea urchins that move on a mat of tiny spines. They use these and cilia to move food or food-coated sand toward a central underslung five-plate mouth to be ground and scraped clean. After life the spines and cilia come off leaving the famous test we find bleached on the sand.

Instead of laying their eggs in water where they could be food for predators, female horned tree frogs (Hemiphractus) gestate their eggs on their back. The eggs hatch as baby froglets, skipping the tadpole stage in a process called direct development.

Bonobos, a species of Great Ape, are native only to the Democratic Republic of Congo. Until 1929, they were assumed to be chimpanzees, with whom they are closely related but have distinct social practices.

Insects (especially caterpillars) form a large part of Black-capped Chickadee diet in summer. The birds hop along tree branches searching for food, sometimes hanging upside down or hovering; they may make short flights to catch insects in the air.

The Malagasy giant jumping rat is only found on Madagascar and can weigh over 1.2 kg (3 lbs)—similar to the weight of a rabbit—making it the island's largest rodent. It can leap close to a metre (over 3 feet) vertically into the air using its strong hind legs.

The golden snub-nosed monkey is an Old World monkey in the subfamily Colobinae. It is endemic to a small area in temperate, mountainous forests of central and Southwest China. They inhabit these mountainous forests of Southwestern China at elevations of 1,500–3,400 m above sea level
The White-whiskered Puffbirds is rare and restricted to the semi-humid deciduous forest of northwest Peru in the Department of Tumbes. They eat insects, and even lizards and frogs.

The Resplendent Quetzal (Pharomachrus mocinno) is a small bird found in southern Mexico and Central America that lives in tropical forests, particularly montane cloud forests. They are part of the family Trogonidae and have two recognized subspecies, P. m. mocinno and P. m. costaricensis.

The harlequin shrimp feeds almost exclusively on starfish. Once it finds a slow starfish, it will flip it on its back to immobilize it and begin eating, starting with all the feet until it reaches the center. Male and female shrimp will team up to pin down large starfish.

Carolina Chickadees hop along tree branches searching for insects, sometimes hanging upside down or hovering; they may make short flights to catch insects in the air. Insects form a large part of their diet, especially in summer; seeds and berries become important in winter.

Seagulls like to eat food that humans have already touched, according to research. Scientists from University of Exeter showed gulls two of the same bits of food, and found the birds are likely to eat the one that they saw a human holding. gulls’ want to eat it as a thing touched it, mean it’s safe.

Bohemian Waxwings can eat huge numbers of berries, each bird sometimes consuming several hundred a day, more than double its own weight. One individual was recorded as eating between 600 and 1,000 cotoneaster berries in six hours, and defecating every four minutes.

The naked mole-rat is eusocial; living in a complex subterranean colony that has one queen, who reproduces, and many fertile workers that maintain and defend the colony - the same social structure as ants and termites. They are also very long-lived rodents - up to 30 years!
The Archerfish (Toxotes jaculatrix) is a living watergun.
The most reliable way to distinguish porpoises from dolphins is by looking at their teeth. Porpoises have more flattened, blade-like teeth distinct from the conical teeth of dolphins.
This is a Bear Cuscus, found on the island of Sulawesi. It's not Civet but actually a marsupial, closely related to Aussie possums.

Giant swallowtail butterflies are the largest species of butterfly in North America, and their caterpillars resemble bird droppings in order to camouflage. They can be found on citrus trees. The one in the photo was one I raised from an egg.
All nuthatches are distinctive when seeking food because they are able to descend tree trunks head-first and can hang upside-down beneath twigs and branches.

The reddish egret is a conspicuously long-legged, long-necked wader of coastal regions of the Americas. It is estimated that there are only 1,500 to 2,000 nesting pairs of reddish egrets in the United States — and most of these are in Texas. Its status is currently listed as "Near Threatened".

The degú (Octodon degus), native to central Chile, is a highly social rodent related to the chinchilla and guinea pig. Also called the common degú, it is herbivorous, mainly feeding on grasses, leaves and seeds. It is listed as "Least Concern". This degú was filmed in the wild near Pudahuel, Chile.
Weighing in at just 3 - 6 ounces, the American kestrel is North America's smallest falcon. Here's one at a local park in Toronto [OC]

Short-eared owls are one of the most widely distributed species of owl in the world. They are found on every continent except Australia and Antarctica and primarily eat small mammals like mice and voles (OC)

Spotted lanternflies are an invasive species to North American, first discovered in Berks County, Pennsylvania in 2014. They are planthoppers and related to cicadas and aphids. Lanternflies suck the sap from plants and are an agricultural pest, harming orchards, vienyards, and even home gardens.
Ruby-crowned kinglets are tiny frenetic bird that constantly flit around but they only spend 10 calories per day

The reason for your cat's reflective eyes in photos is called the "tapetum lucidum". It's a light reflective layer behind the retina, causing it to practically receive light twice. It's the reason cats (among other predators) have night vision.

Adult fireflies evolved their glow to attract mates, not to ward off predators. Mature fireflies lit their lanterns before birds and bats evolved, suggesting that sexual signalling drove this dazzling behaviour.

Bronze-winged jacanas are polyandrous. The female forms harem territories, consisting of the territories of 1-4 males. Before laying eggs the female may spend more time with a receiver male. After laying eggs, the receiver male takes over the responsibility of brooding & raising chicks.

Victoria crowned pigeons have different calls. Their contact call is a deep, muffled, and rather human-like 'ummm' or 'hmmm'. Their mating calls consist of a deep 'hoota-hoota-hoota-hoota-hoota' sound. When defending their territories, these birds make a resounding 'whup-up, whup-up, whup-up' call.

The marbled polecat is a small mammal belonging to the monotypic genus Vormela within the mustelid subfamily Ictonychinae. Vormela is from the German word Würmlein, which means "little worm". The specific name peregusna comes from perehuznya, which is Ukrainian for "polecat"
The Arctic Tern travels between the North and South Pole very year, due to this it sees more daylight than any other animal.
Not to be confused with the smaller Muskrat or the paddle-tailed Beaver, the similarly semi-aquatic Nutria also lives in creeks and wetlands in much of the Americas

After 20 years of trying, the Kroombit tinkerfrog was first bred in captivity in 2020 at Currumbin Wildlife Sanctuary, numbering 84 frogs just a year later, a vital insurance population. In the wild, this species is critically endangered, thought to number around 200 individuals in Kroombit Tops NP.

Northern cardinals are preyed upon by a wide variety of predators native to North America, including falcons, all Accipiter hawks, shrikes, bald eagles, golden eagles and several owls, including long-eared owls, and eastern screech owls.

The hummingbird can lap up nectar up to 20 times per second. Its forked tongue traps nectar with hair-like extensions called lamellae. The lamellae extend outward when the separated tongue is elongated, and roll inward upon retraction. This autonomous fluid trapping process requires no energy.
Plesiosaurs are widely believed to nurture their young, due to the enormous size of their young at birth and their use of protected nurseries to give birth.

Dogs "see" the world through their noses. Studies have revealed that unlike any other animal studied, dogs have neural connections between the smell system and the vision system. There other connections to cortices including those for spatial memory and the area for emotion. Image u/Michaelarobards

The wings of butterflies and other lepidopterans are covered with scales. The coloration of butterflies like this blue morpho result from the pigmentation and the light scattering effects of these scales.

Plume Moths (Pterophoridae) are named for their exquisite wings. Like most other lepidopterans they have a herbivorous larval stage and some species have been used as a biocontrol agent against weeds. You may know them from looking like a stray IUD

The African dwarf crocodile is among the smallest crocodilians and is the smallest species of crocodile. It has a typical adult size of less than a 100 lb (45 Kg) and a maximum length of 6.2 ft (1.9m).

The black currawong (Strepera fuliginosa), also known locally as the black jay, is a large passerine bird endemic to Tasmania. One of three currawong species in the genus Strepera, it is closely related to the butcherbirds and Australian magpie within the family Artamidae.
Golden pheasant use “lateral display” in courtship display, which means the male showing the profile to female, spreading feather in an unsymmetrcal way.

The European goldfinch's preferred food is small seeds such as those from thistles (the Latin name is from Carduus, a genus of thistles), cornflowers, and teasels, but insects are also taken when feeding young. It also regularly visits bird feeders in winter.
I went to an aquarium and learned all sorts of facts about this beautiful Lionfish, my favorites being that its spines are extremely venomous, and it can expand its stomachs up to 30 times in size!

Spotted hyenas are a long-lived carnivore species that have an average lifespan of 12 years if they reach puberty, although they can reach up to 26 years. Due to their skull being so heavily reinforced, it takes on average 35 months before it reaches adult size, a year after puberty. [photo: OC]

Pink-eared ducks, native to Australia, are spatulate-billed waterfowl closely related to shelducks. Their bills are well designed for straining mollusks, crustaceans, insects, algae and plankton. Nesting is stimulated by the drying and filling of pools that promote the growth of their food sources.

The Emerald Ash Borer has destroyed millions of ash trees in North America since its introduction in 2002. Adults fly impressive distances, but they can also be transported by firewood. They have recently been found in Oregon. The iridescent coloration is characteristic of the jewel beetle family.

Female southern cassowary typically lays about 4 bright green eggs in a clutch. Incubation, which is exclusively done by the males, lasts for 47 to 61 days. Once the chicks hatch they stay with their father until they become independent at about nine months.
