The small black and white Willie Wagtail (Rhipidura leucophrys) is hard to miss. these small territorial birds will often harass much larger birds such as the laughing kookaburra, magpies, ravens even pet cats and dogs

Greater gliders are the world's largest marsupial gliders. They use their furry membranes to glide distances of 100 metres (330 ft) between eucalyptus trees in the forests of eastern Australia. They will also wrap themselves up in their membranes, using them like blankets, to stay warm.

Dumbo octopuses move by slowly flapping their ear-like fins; they use their arms to steer. They are foraging predators and eat pelagic invertebrates that swim above the sea floor. Unlike most octopuses, the Dumbo octopus doesn’t have an ink sac because it rarely encounters predators in the deep sea

Tree-kangaroos are marsupials of the genus Dendrolagus, adapted for arboreal locomotion. They inhabit the tropical rainforests of New Guinea and far northeastern Queensland, along with some of the islands in the region. They are the only true arboreal macropods.

The combination of the Vietnamese mossy frog's green body, black spots, tubercles and spines makes it look like a clump of moss, which it spends a large portion of its time pretending to be. Native to Vietnam, these frogs live in mossy caves and in the banks of rocky mountain streams.

The spring migration of the King Eider can involve huge flocks. Two observers at Point Barrow, the northernmost point of land in the United States, once counted 360,000 King Eiders passing in just 10 hours, with 113,000 of those in just 30 minutes alone.

Leatherback sea turtles can grow to the size of a small car - with a length of 1.8m (almost 6 feet) and 500kg (over 1000 pounds) but have been recorded at 3m (almost ten feet) and nearly a ton (over 2000 pounds). They are the largest turtle and heaviest non-crocodilian reptiles.

The Java sparrow is about 15 to 17 cm (5.9 to 6.7 in) in length from the beak to its tip of tail feathers. Although only about the size of a house sparrow, it may be the largest species in the estrildid family.
Regal Jumping Spiders can take down prey 2 to 3 times their size - including small frogs and lizards!

The endangered cotton-top tamarin lives in a small area of northwestern Colombia that is currently threatened by deforestation. They have claw-like nails, which are critical to jumping from tree to tree in their forest habitat.

Pyrrhuloxia is a benefit to cotton fields, as it assists in eating populations of cotton worms and weevils. This species of cardinal also visits bird feeders and in the winter forages in huge flocks, sometimes numbering in the thousands.

The puff adder is an expert ambush predator that is responsible for the most snakebite fatalities in the whole of Africa. This snake is believed to employ chemical crypsis, able to completely conceal its scent, making it even harder to find. This is the only case of a vertebrate organism doing so.

Pavement ants (Tetramorium spp.) form large colonies, containing over 10,000 workers. They will fight unrelated colonies for territory and resources. The losing colony will be raided for eggs, and the ants that hatch from the spoils will become workers for the new colony.
The Poland is an old chicken breed. Eggs should be collected a couple of times a day to prevent egg eating (for some reason, Polands do like to peck an egg).

Arguably the most active of all dolphins, dusky dolphins are known for their energetic, skillful leaping and tumbling acrobatics. They see each other better in the air to help synchronize cooperative movements for herding prey. Here, a pod one thousand strong off the Kaikōura coast of New Zealand

The white-breasted nuthatch is omnivorous, eating insects and seeds. It places large food items such as acorns or hickory nuts in crevices in tree trunks, and then hammers them open with its strong beak; surplus seeds are cached under loose bark or crevices of trees.

Blakiston’s fish owls love dense forests with hoary trees (full of nesting nooks) near lakes, rivers, springs, and shoals that don’t freeze over in winter. They love fish but they’ll eat small mammals and other birds, too, especially in winter.
Birds have 7 different feather types ranging from flight (wing) feathers to small filoplumes and bristles that act like whiskers to sense and protect the face

The veiled chameleon gets its name from the bony protusion atop its head, which is called a casque. Both males and females sport the fancy headgear, which serves to channel water droplets down into the reptiles’ mouths, a crucial adaptation in their dry habitats.

This is the giant garter snake, thamnophis gigas. As it's name suggests, it's been observed growing up to 5 feet long, making it the biggest species of garter snake. They're native to Central California, and are sadly a threatened species due to the rapid loss of their wetland habitat.

Coprophanaeus lancifer is a large species of tunneling dung beetle found in the Amazon basin. Both males & females of this species boast a long cephalic horn, w/c they use to fight other members of their sex.Despite its name, this insect prefers to eat carrion vs dung. An important ecosystem engr

Horned frogs are large, squat, and aggressive. They remain motionless and wait for prey to wander by; attempting to eat anything that will fit into their mouths, as well as things that don't. They are also called PacMan frogs due to their round shape, large mouth, and habit of swallowing prey whole.

The go-away-birds are crested aves named for the noisy and repetitive calls that they often make when disturbed. Their vocalizations range from a "kow-kow" call to one that sounds vaguely like "go-awayyy", with a drawl on the last syllable.

Japanese macaques survive the cold by bathing in natural hot springs. Competition for space is tough, there is a strict dominance hierarchy with one family in charge. High-ranked macaques may drag underlings out of the spring into the cold. Coups occur often as well as competition within families.

All hummingbirds are small, and many are minute. Even the largest, the giant hummingbird (Patagona gigas) of western South America, is only about 20 cm (8 inches) long, with a body weight of about 20 g (0.7 ounce), less than that of most sparrows.

Hoverflies are important pollinators of wildflowers in many ecosystems and are responsible for the pollination of numerous species of flowering plants that produce food for wildlife. Their larvae feed on aphids and other plant pests. This hoverfly is feeding on the nectar of garlic flowers.

Flamingos are large birds that are identifiable by their long necks, sticklike legs and pink or reddish feathers. Flamingos embody the saying "you are what you eat." The pink and reddish colors of a flamingo's feathers come from eating pigments found in algae and invertebrates.

Flocks of galahs often congregate and forage on the ground for food in open, grassy areas. Flocks of independent juvenile galahs will often disperse from their birth flock haphazardly. The galah feeds on seeds gathered on the ground, mainly feeding in the morning and late afternoon.

The aardwolf (alphabetically the second creature) are a monogamous species of hyena that mostly eats termites with their long sticky tongue. They will raise their cubs for up to a year as a pair, with the male watching the child for up to 6 hours a night while their mother finds food

Some Lizards within the group Anguimorpha can breath through the process of gular pumping, this leaves the musculatur of the ribcage free to assist in running. Due to this abillity those are the only lizards able to basically running their prey to exaustion in a head on charge.

Ermine moths are named after the white fur with black spots worn by royals and their court. At around this time of the year some species (Small Ermines, not shown) form communal halloween-style cobwebs that engulf hedges and trees and protect the caterpillars as they grow. More in comments.

The silvery marmoset is a New World monkey that lives in the eastern Amazon Rainforest in Brazil. The fur of the silvery marmoset is colored whitish silver-grey except for a dark tail. its naked flesh-colored ears stand out from the fur as well.

Rufous Hummingbirds have the hummingbird gift for fast, darting flight and pinpoint maneuverability. They are pugnacious birds that tirelessly chase away other hummingbirds, even in places they’re only visiting on migration. Like other hummers, they eat insects as well as nectar.

Often mistaken as dragonflies, damselflies belong to the same order (Odonata) but are usually distinguished by their thinner, needlelike abdomens and by the way they hold their wings when at rest. In Japan, they are revered and respected, being symbolic of happiness, strength, courage and success.

The bog turtle is North America's smallest turtle, with a diminutive maximum size of 11 cm (4.5 inches) and an average weight of 110 grams (3.9 oz). It lives in marshes and bogs, burrowing into soft mud to escape predators, as its shell offers little defense. It is considered critically endangered.

The Australian white ibis' range of food includes both terrestrial and aquatic invertebrates and human scraps. The most favoured foods are crayfish and mussels, which the bird obtains by digging with its long bill.

Malayan Tapirs are the only species of tapir found outside of South/Central America. Despite their chunky appearance, Malayan Tapirs are not only great swimmers, but excellent climbers capable of scaling steep slopes!

The Spotted Turtle is native to the USA and Canada. Their sex is uniquely temperature dependent, meaning the external temperature during incubation influences resulting sex. Warmer temperatures produce females while cooler temperatures produce males!
Largest of its kind, Therizinosaurus evolved from predators that traded off eating meat for a primarily herbivorous diet. They have to the largest claws of any animal on Earth. (Prehistoric Planet)
Canada goose goslings leave the nest when they're 1-2 days old and can already walk, swim, feed, and dive

The firefly produces light in the presence of oxygen, magnesium, and adenosine triphosphate by using an enzyme, luciferase, to oxidize a complex organic compound, luciferin. The light produced is often referred to as "cold light."

California scrub jays, like many other corvids, exploit ephemeral surpluses by storing food in scattered caches within their territories. They rely on highly accurate and complex memories to recover the hidden caches, often after long periods of time.

The North American Porcupine. Contrary to popular belief, they don’t throw their quills. Rather, the superficial quills easily detached when in contact with a predator. This can also be aided by a swing of their tail!

Most butterflies can only sip fluids with their specialized mouth parts, but zebra longwings’ saliva enables them to dissolve pollen and take in protein. Because of this, longwings continue to live and lay eggs for several months, while other butterflies live only a few weeks
Though it swims like a fish and is vaguely fish-shaped, the glassy nautilus (Carinaria cristata) is actually a sea elephant, a type of free-swimming predatory snail.

The eastern bluebird is a small North American migratory thrush found in open woodlands, farmlands, and orchards. The bright-blue breeding plumage of the male, easily observed on a wire or open perch, makes this species a favorite of birders. It is the state bird of Missouri and New York.

Female elephant mosquitoes (Toxorhynchites spp.) do not need a blood meal to lay eggs! As larvae they prey upon other larval mosquitoes and get enough protein to produce eggs as adults. Adults are pollinators and feed on nectar and other sugars.

Honduran White Bat. One of the most distinctive features of this bat is its white fur, which helps it to blend in with the white tents it constructs for roosting. The bat uses its sharp teeth to cut the veins of large leaves, causing them to fold inwards and form a tent-like structure.

Like most species, the eurasian jay's diet changes with the seasons but is noteworthy for its prolific caching of food—especially oak acorns and beechnuts—for winter and spring. While caching occurs throughout the year, it is most intense in the autumn.
The broad-tailed hummingbird is found from Guatemala to Mexico, and western United States and Western Canada during summer, while wintering regions are mainly in southern Mexico and Guatemala

Unlike Domestic Dogs, Dingoes Only Breed Once A Year Between March To May. Only Dominant Members Of A Pack Will Successfully Mate & Raise Pups, While The Others Help Take Care Of Them Until The Next Breeding Season.

Hedgehogs spread substances with strange odour on their body, which called self-anointing. We don't quite know the function of self-anointing, adult hedgehogs do it in breeding season, so it might be a sexual signal.
The Scottish Crossbill (Loxia Scotica) is the only bird that is endemic (native and restricted) to the UK.

While king penguins prefer to live on islands south of the Polar Front, they prefer to fish in waters just north of it where surface air temperatures are around 4.5 degrees C. They have been known to dive to a maximum of 322 meters.

Despite the similarities that male seahorses share with female mammals and reptiles during pregnancy, seahorse fathers have a unique way of giving birth to their young. They seem to rely on elaborate behaviours and their unique body structure to facilitate labour.

The European wildcat (Felis silvestris) is a species of forest dwelling wildcat from Europe and western Asia. They are closely related, but not directly ancestral to house cats. They mainly feed on small mammals like rodents, but will also hunt mustelids and larger prey like deer fawns.

The great bustard is the heaviest bird in the world capable of flight. It can weigh up to 21 kg (46 lb) - about the weight of a 5 year old child. Males will grow colorful breeding plumage each year, including moustachial feathers on each side of the beak that can be 20 cm long in old males.

White breasted nuthatches would cache a seed under a loose bark of a tree or a moss to survive through the winter. They'd also steal from other birds stashes, so they tend to approach their own in discreet and from the opposite side of that tree

Mononykus is a small insectivorous dinosaur that used it's sickle-shaped claws to prey upon insect nests to feed, it was likely a desert/scrubland specialist and was among the largest members of its family. (Prehistoric Planet)
Two-toed sloths, unlike most mammals, have hair that grows from their belly to their back, which allows rain to run off of them while they hang in trees.

Silky anteaters are the smallest living anteaters. The animal’s maximum overall length is about 44 cm (17 inches). About one-half of that length is the furred prehensile tail. Silky anteaters are found in southern Mexico, and Central and South America.
This is the smallest chameleon in the world, otherwise known as the "Brookesia nana". Males can grow up to .55 inches while females are typically .75 inches!
The tufted titmouse gathers food from the ground and from tree branches, frequently consuming a variety of berries, nuts, seeds, small fruits, insects, and other invertebrates.

Bluebirds feed by perching on a high point, such as a branch or fence post, and swooping down to catch insects on or near the ground. The availability of a winter food source will often determine whether or not a bird will migrate. If bluebirds do remain in a region for the winter, they group and se
Harvestmen (Opiliones) are not spiders and do not have venom. Some are capable of producing some chemical defenses, similar to a tiny, 8-legged skunk. If you try to pull their leg, it will fall off.

The Common Green Lacewing: these tiny insects pupate within loosely-woven cocoons measuring just 3-6mm (about 1/8 to 1/4 inch) in diameter; the lacewing spends about 5 days maturing inside, and then it cuts an opening in the top of the cacoon and emerges as a fully-developed adult
The mourning cloak butterfly has a long lifespan of 11-12 months and will hibernate over the winter. As a defense against predators, adults will play dead.
Ring-necked Pheasants sometimes cope with extreme cold by simply remaining dormant for days at a time.

The Eurasian nuthatch eats mainly insects, particularly caterpillars and beetles, although in autumn and winter its diet is supplemented with nuts and seeds. The nuthatch can forage when descending trees head first, as well as when climbing.

The Yellow Rumped Warbler, commonly known as a “Butterbutt”, mostly eats insects but will eat fruit such as juniper berries, especially in winter. This one is probably going for the mealworms in my mom’s feeder.
The Cunningham's Skink uses its protruding scales and bloated body to defensively lodge itself inside of crevices. They are native to Australia and can reach lengths of up to 30 cm.

The common starling is largely insectivorous and feeds on both pest and other arthropods. The food range includes spiders, crane flies, moths, mayflies, dragonflies, damsel flies, grasshoppers, earwigs, lacewings, caddisflies, flies, beetles, sawflies, bees, wasps and ants.

Pygmy slow loris population is declining as a result of habitat degradation and illegal trade. Association of Zoos and Aquariums established a plan to breed them in zoo, here is a pygmy slow loris born at Columbus Zoo.

The Kakapo loves to "Party:" Males perform a courtship ritual known as 'lekking' where they dig shallow bowls in the ground, over which they emit a low-frequency "BOOM" sound that can be heard up to 5 km away, similar to a bass drum inviting potential mates to the party!!
Colonial courtship/breeding is well documented in non-avian Theropod Dinosaurs from nests to designated display areas.

The wolverine, a relative of the mink and weasel, is the largest terrestrial member of the family Mustelidae. Its scientific name is Gulo gulo, meaning “glutton it’s also known as carcajou, or quickhatch.

The common name for the red-winged blackbird is taken from the mainly black adult male's distinctive red shoulder patches, or epaulets, which are visible when the bird is flying or displaying. At rest, the male also shows a pale yellow wingbar.

The Asiatic Lion is 10-20% smaller than their African cousin, with a larger tail tuft, a distinct belly fold & a smaller mane in males. Their former range stretched across Northern Africa, Greece, South-West Asia & Eastern India but is now confined to the Gir Forest Preserve of Gujurat, India.

The American crow is omnivorous. It will feed on invertebrates of all types, carrion, scraps of human food, fruits, nuts such as walnuts and almonds, seeds, eggs and nestlings, stranded fish on the shore and various grains. American crows are active hunters and will prey on mice, young rabbits, etc.
Jumping spiders have excellent vision. They can see in color, and their visual acuity is comparable to that of a cat.
The Brandt's Bat: this species holds the world record for longevity among bats, as researchers in Siberia once documented a Brandt's bat that had been living in the wild for at least 41 years

The violet sabrewing (Campylopterus hemileucurus) is a species of hummingbird in the tribe Trochilini, sometimes known as the emeralds. It is the largest hummingbird of Mexico and Central America, being 13 to 15 centimetres (5 to 6 in) long with a weight of 9 to 12 grams (0.3 to 0.4 oz).

Honey Possum is one of the world smallest marsupial. They come from western Australia and the only nectarivores mammal that are not a bat. One of their favorite flower is Banksia. These guys are common and not endangered

The great curassow (Crax rubra ) is a large, pheasant-like bird from the Neotropical rainforests, its range extending from eastern Mexico, through Central America to western Colombia and northwestern Ecuador. Male birds are black with curly crests and yellow beaks; females are often colorful.

Eurylepta californica looks like it's had chocolate drizzled on it. Each flatworm is an hermaphrodite carrying both sperm and eggs. There is a cost associated with growing young so a mating couple engages in penis fencing trying to hypodermically impregnate the other before getting poked themselves.

The peacock spiders belonging to the jumping spider family is mainly indigenous to different parts of Australia. The colorful body patterns displayed by the males, along with their amazing dancing skills have earned them their name.

The common blackbird (Turdus merula) is a species of true thrush. It is also called the Eurasian blackbird (especially in North America, to distinguish it from the unrelated New World blackbirds), or simply the blackbird where this does not lead to confusion with a similar-looking local species.

The Goonch Catfish (Bagarius yarrelli) is a freshwater megafish that can grow up to 2m long. They were considered so culturally important in the Mughal Empire that The Order Of The Fish, the highest honour for a Mughal soldier, was named after them.

Bluebirds feed by perching on a high point, such as a branch or fence post, and swooping down to catch insects on or near the ground. The availability of a winter food source will often determine whether or not a bird will migrate.

The Ashy Gecko (Sphaerodactylus elegans) is a dwarf gecko reaching a maximum size of 8cm. The Cuban subspecies was once believed to be 2 separate species because of the stark difference between juveniles & adults. The Haitian variant’s appearance is only slightly more similar across life stages

One of the largest squid species, the 7 ft Dana octopus squid is a very rare sight. Their tennis ball-sized "headlights" are their most distinctive feature, large photophore organs at the end of two of their arms. Scientists think they use these to stun prey and navigate in the inky depths.

Though one of the speediest fliers of the small birds species, Ruby Throated Hummingbirds have extremely short legs. Due to this, they’re unable to hop or walk so instead they shuffle about when traveling on land.

Fishers are mustelids common across Canada and northeastern USA. They feed on a variety of small animals, and are one of the few predators of porcupines. Fishers have partially retractable claws that make them agile and speedy tree climbers, capable of jumping up to 7 feet between trees.

The Cape francolin is a bird of scrubby open areas, preferably close to running water. It breeds in spring and early summer, when it is also most vocal. Its nest is a grass-lined scrape under a bush, and six to eight eggs are laid (but sometimes two females will lay in one nest).
Bumblebees Use Electric Fields to Find Nectar

The Java sparrow is about 5.9 to 6.7 in in length from the beak to its tip of tail feathers. Although only the size of a house sparrow, it may be the largest species in the estrildid family. The mean body mass is 0.86 oz, making it heavier than its nearest known rival, the black-belled seedeater.

What is a Dingo, exactly? For decades scientists have puzzled over the origin of Australia’s wild canines, and today the most widely accepted theory is that they are descended from early Asian dog breeds that marooned on the continent and adapted to become its new top land predator.

Waxy Monkey Tree Frog. In the tropical forest of South America, there is an interesting frog - the two-colored phyllomedusa. Large, green, as if covered with wax, with a very peculiar manner of moving. It secretes a skin secretion rich in bioactive peptides that are often used in local rituals.

Oviraptor was a bird like dinosaur who’s name means “egg thief” due to the first individual being found atop a nest. Later research proved this was in fact the dinosaurs own nest, which was the first solid evidence of parental behavior in non-avian dinosaurs.

Did you know that there's a proven link between performance in showjumping horses and the colour of the jumps? Due to their dichromatic vision and bad depth of field, horses may be reluctant to certain colours or combinations of jumps, which could be why the horses get so stressed!

The Olm, also known as the proteus is a unique species of troglobitic salamander native to caves in the Dinaric Alps in Europe. They are completely blind, have reduced digits on their feet, and can possibly live for more then 100 years.

Bat hawks are the dark, feather-clad vampire hunters of the birds of prey. They begin their hunt for bats, their main prey, at dusk as the bats emerge from their roost; catching them at high speeds mid-flight and swallowing them whole.

RATS MAY LAUGH IF TICKLED… “Researchers found not all rats like to be tickled and that some rats emitted very high numbers of calls whilst others did not, and these calls are directly related with their emotional experience”
The only hummingbird species regularly found in eastern North America is the ruby-throated hummingbird, but they have the largest breeding range of all North American hummingbirds!

Red Necked Keelback—This reptile is the lone genus of snakes on this planet that displays the twin effect of venomous and Poisonous features at the same time (The poison oozes from the neck glands and it delivers its deadly venom through its rear fangs).

Sabethes cyaneus is a mosquito found in tropical rainforests in South America and Costa Rica. Males do an elaborate mating dance to attract females, but attraction goes both ways. If females are missing their feathery leg warmers males will refuse to mate with them.

Brazilian guinea pig, closely related to the domesticated guinea pig, can be found in savannah and disturbed habitats across much of South America. The two species have been bred together, but many of the female offspring are infertile.

Loud and constant chirpers, Rosy-faced Lovebirds are very social animals and often congregate in small groups in the wild. They eat throughout the day and take frequent baths. Coloration can vary widely among populations. Plumage is identical in males and females.
Melibe leonina, or lion's mane nudibranch, is a predatory sea slug, it use the Venus flytrap-like oral hood to catch prey.
Reindeer calves are able to stand few minutes after birth and can follow their mothers around, but they will stay hidden for the first week of their life
The ovenbird is a large warbler that gets its name from the distinct oven shaped nests they build (OC)
The hard bony carapace of smooth trunkfish, Lactophrys triqueter, can generate trimming force, to keep them move stable in complex aquatic environment.
Blue-tailed day gecko, Phelsuma cepediana, is a species endemic to Mauritius. It's the only pollinator of the critically endangered plant Roussea simplex.

Honeybees can reach 44°C 111°F without injury. They decouple their wings and buzz their wing muscles on full power to get hot and then go into empty cells next to pupae to warm them up. Their precise temperature regulation determines the role of each pupa with 34°C = housekeeper 35°C = forager.
Crested geckos were thought to be extinct until their rediscovery in 1994. They are currently listed as vulnerable, with their biggest threats being invasive fire ants

Picasso triggerfish (Rhinecanthus aculeatus) is a species of Tetraodontiformes. It get the name because it’s colorful appearance. Although looks funny, those fish are very fierce when guarding their eggs.
The rare Marquesan monarch faces further endangerment from hunting by feral cats and the polynesian rat, both of which are non-native introduced species to the island of Mohotani.
The Clark's Nutcracker has a special pouch under its tongue that it uses to carry seeds long distances. The nutcracker harvests seeds from pine trees and takes them away to hide them for later use.

Turtles can be separated into two suborders: Pleurodira ("side necks"), who tuck their heads to one side when withdrawing, and Cryptodira ("hidden necks"), who pull their heads in between their forelegs. Pictured is an Indian Flapshell Turtle, one of the latter.

Pavement ants (Tetramorium caespitum) engage in territorial disputes aka ANT WARS. The fallen may be cannibalized. Hidden underground, nests can range for 5-6 meters, but tiny piles of dirt in sidewalk cracks betrays their presence.
The Blue-headed Vireo is the only vireo within its range that makes extensive use of coniferous forests, although it also occupies deciduous habitats.
Hummingbirds Gather Spider Silk to Build Their Nests, The Silk Both Insulates And Expands to Fit The Growing Chicks

Parasitic Horsfield's bronze-cuckoo (Chalcites basalis) lay eggs in superb fairy-wren (Malurus cyaneus) nest. Mother fairy-wren call to their eggs, after hatched, fairy-wren chicks will imitate the voice of their mom. So fairy-wren can detect foreign cuckoo chicks.

A female Northern Cardinal is fawn-colored, with mostly grayish-brown tones and a slight reddish tint on the wings, crest, and tail feathers. Their face mask is gray to black and is less defined than that of the male. Both sexes possess prominent raised crests and bright coral-colored beaks.

Female red-winged blackbirds tend to stay low, prowling through the vegetation and building their nests. They can be found in home gardens, particularly during their migration, if seeds have been scattered on the ground. The forest curtains serve as a resting place during the day.
Butterflies originated in North America after splitting from moths, new study suggests

The saffron finch (Sicalis flaveola) is a tanager from South America that is common in open and semi-open areas in lowlands outside the Amazon Basin. Although commonly regarded as a canary, it is not related to the Atlantic canary.
Swainson’s Thrushes have been called “mosquito thrushes” for their flycatching habit of going after flying insects while feeding on their breeding grounds.

It was thought that nectar concentration by honeybees only took place in the hive but it seems that bees don't waste time. The process of turning nectar into honey begins on the flower and continues during the flight home so that water is reduced and sugar concentration goes up. (More in comments)

Albatrosses hardly expend any energy when soaring 1000s miles over the ocean. They take advantage of the speed difference that occurs in a boundary layer of air above the sea. By sailing down from the higher speed air and turning like a ribbon near the slow air above the sea they ride back up again.
The hoatzin of Venezuela smells like fresh cow manure . Zoologists have discovered why: it has a stomach like a cow’s. The hoatzin holds its food in the gut for as long as 43 hours.

The white-winged duck occurs in dense tropical evergreen forests, near rivers and swamps. Although they have been found to do well in dimly lit and shady conditions, they also have a higher risk of contracting avian tuberculosis. Only about 800 remain in the wild.

Pangolins have no teeth; instead they rely on a gizzard-like stomach that is adapted for grinding food. A pangolin’s tongue can be up to 16 inches in length. They use these extraordinarily long tongues to reach insects burrowed underground.
The Soprano Pipistrelle is named for its elegant songs. They may eat up to 3000 small insects in a night. They were first described only about twenty years ago.
Black-winged stilt (Himantopus himantopus) is a widely distributed very long-legged wader in the avocet and stilt family (Recurvirostridae) | Serengeti | Tanzania | Nikon D850 | [OC]

The saiga antelope, or saiga, is a critically endangered antelope which once inhabited a vast area of the Eurasian steppe spanning the foothills of the Carpathian Mountains in the northwest and Caucasus in the southwest into Mongolia and further. This antelope also once ranged into North America.

Eurasian bullfinch's food is mainly seeds and buds of fruit trees, which can make it a pest in orchards. If wild bird cover is planted for it, kale, quinoa and millet are preferred, next to tall hedges or woodland.

The Hawaiian Monk Seal is the only seal native to Hawaii, and is also the only marine animal found solely in the US. It is one of the most endangered seals in the world with a population of 1,400. However recently their population has begun recovering and is growing at 2% a year!

The Yellow Loosestrife Bee (Macropis europaea) is a solitary bee that nests in burrows on wetlands. It harvests oil from the Yellow Loosestrife flower and uses it to waterproof its brood cells, in each of which it lays an egg. More oil is used to close the cell saving growing bees from drowning.

Dusky-legged guan eats fruit, flowers and buds taken from the ground or plucked from tree branches, and acts as a seed disperser for various species of trees and palms, such as the endangered palm Euterpe edulis, or the palms of the genus Syagrus (e.g. queen palm and licuri)

Flickers may be observed in open habitats near trees, including woodlands, edges, yards, and parks. In the western United States, one can find them in mountain forests all the way up to tree line. Northern flickers generally nest in holes in trees like other woodpeckers.

Female Anna's hummingbirds use plant down and spider webs to build cup shaped nests approximately 1.5 inch diameter. They often decorate the outside with lichen or moss. Typically clutches are 2 eggs with a 16 day incubation and 20 day nestling period

The Malabar large-spotted civet (Viverra civettina), also known as the Malabar civet, is a viverrid endemic to the Western Ghats of India. It is listed as Critically Endangered on the IUCN Red List as the population is estimated to number fewer than 250 mature individuals.

Meet Mbiresaurus Raathi, one of the oldest dinosaurs ever found. It lived in Triassic period (Carnian age) about 230 million years ago and lived in what is now Zimbabwe. It was an early type of sauropodomorph, a group of herbivorous long-necked dinosaurs.While small it had long arms, legs and neck.

The researchers showed that male bottlenose dolphins form the largest multilevel alliance network known outside humans. These collaborative relationships between groups increase male dolphins’ access to controversial resources.

Sunda colugo, found throughout southeast Asia, is actually not a lemur and does not fly, but instead, it glides as it leaps between trees. The colugo can glide over 100 m with minimal loss in elevation. Colugos are generally nocturnal.
Wavy Bubble Snails (Micromelo undatas) primarily eat polychaete worms. The toxins from these worms become incorporated into the snail's tissues and are then used for the bubble snail's own defense.

Zombie ant fungus (Ophiocordyceps unilateralis) compels ants to leave their nest for a more humid microclimate that’s favorable to the fungus’s growth. The ant clamps onto the underside of a leaf, dies, then the fungus uses the nutrients gained from the ant to create a fruiting body to spread spores

The palm cockatoo (Probosciger aterrimus) is a large black species of cockatoo in the parrot family (Cacatuidae) native to New Guinea, the Aru Islands, and Cape York Peninsula in Queensland. It has a very large black beak and prominent red cheek patches.

Banana slug, Redwood NP, California. The Pacific banana slug (genus Ariolimax) of western North America is the second-largest species of terrestrial slug in the world, growing up to 25 centimetres (9.8 in) long,[6] and weights of 115 grams (4.1 ounces).

Tasmanian Tiger hair glows blue under ultraviolet light. Instead of just the chocolate, honey and grey colours visible to us, Australian creatures able to see into this part of the spectrum would have had a very different experience of Thylacine markings. Article, audio and images in comments.

The Sable Antelope is a large Antelope native to East and South Africa. They are most noteworthy for their large, backwards facing horns. Mature males live alone, while females live in small family herds. this group of females was photographed at Busch Gardens Tampa!

The vestibular system in birds are much better developed and serve as internal gyroscopes and accelerometers with significantly more precision. Pair this information with having more vertebrae and neck muscles and it can be, if the bird wants to, effectively act like a gimbal.
A quiet little town of around 220 permanent residents in Australia is under siege by a growing mob of kangaroos.

Morticia is a Corpse Flower who recently bloomed at the Cincinnati Zoo & Botanical Garden. The corpse flower only blooms once every 5-10 years and it possesses a distinct odor that smells of rotting flesh. It does this in order to attract pollinators that are attracted to the smell of dead animals.

Bear cuscuses are only found on the Indonesian island Sulawesia and some smaller nearby islands. They have evolved in isolation from other marsupials. Their main food are leaves with low nutrional value so they have developed a very energy-efficient lifestyle.

The Southern Darwin frog is a rare, tiny, (max size of 3.5cm) leaf-shaped amphibian. This frog has an odd brooding habit. The male frog carries and incubates his tadpoles in his specialized vocal sac for 6 weeks until they hatch. Then, when the time is right papa frog will spew them out as froglets.
A blue-gray gnatcatcher builds a nest held together by spiderwebs and decorated with lichen. These tiny songbird’s nests are smaller than a hockey puck!
A chick of the philippine eagle (also known as monkey-eating eagle) being fed through a hand puppet that resembles its parents. There are only around 250 breeding pairs left of this species.

The black and rufous elephant shrew is a small, particularly skittish mammal which uses its long proboscis to flip through leaf litter on the ground; looking for insects and scooping them up with a long tongue.
